#let lesson = (
title: [Advanced Turning]

,aim: [
Perform steep turns and manage turning upsets at angles of bank up to 60°, maintaining full situational awareness and aircraft control throughout.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 4.2 continues the student-as-PIC phase. The instructor operates as an observer for all trained flight portions, assuming the instructor role only to introduce and demonstrate advanced turning. Advanced turning builds directly on E6 (Basic Turning) and introduces steep turns at 60° AoB, slipping turns, spiral dive recognition and recovery, dutch roll turn reversals, and sustained 360° turns. These manoeuvres pair with E6 to satisfy the two-flight requirement for turning competency. Skidding turns are discussed for awareness but are not practiced by the student — no "pro-spin" inputs by the student are required in this training.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Explain how load factor increases with angle of bank and the resulting effect on stall speed
- Describe the visual and instrument indications of a spiral dive, and explain why it must not be confused with a steep turn
- Explain the recovery from a spiral dive: close throttle, level wings, ease out of the dive
- Explain why rolling wings level must precede any pitch change in a nose-low recovery
- Describe the cause and effect of slipping and skidding in turns, and the visual illusions and stalling risks associated with each
- Describe the significance of elevated stall speed in level turns

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Enter, maintain, and exit a level turn at 45° and 60° AoB, maintaining altitude ±100 ft and airspeed ±10 kts
- Maintain appropriate coordination throughout all turns
- Identify and recover from a spiral dive: close throttle, level wings, ease out of the dive
- Demonstrate a deliberate slipping turn; recover to coordinated flight
- Execute turn reversals (dutch rolls) at 20° AoB
- Maintain a sustained 360° turn at 45° and 60° AoB to a nominated heading within ±10°

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] HASSELL before the manoeuvre sequence begins, then every 15 minutes; maintain continuous height, traffic and airspace awareness throughout steep turns
- [TEM] Pre-brief threats: spatial disorientation, G-loading, overbanking, minimum height, controlled airspace encroachment
- [HF] Proprioceptive illusions and parallax error — trust instruments over body sensation; parallax error is especially noticeable in steep turns; brief startle management for spiral dive simulation
- [CRM] Student briefs the flight as PIC; instructor is observer; all decisions are the student's
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — sideslip, skid and slip *(Pg 105, 167)*
- Aerodynamics — load factor, stalling speed in turns *(Pg 165–166)*
- Aerodynamics — spiral dive cause, recognition and recovery *(Pg 106)*
- Human Factors — illusion of slipping/skidding, disorientation *(Pg 168)*
- Human Factors — SA, stress and decision-making *(Pg 3, 36)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Pre-brief: spatial disorientation, overbanking, G-loading, minimum height, controlled airspace encroachment
- [SA] HASSELL before the manoeuvre sequence begins, then every 15 minutes; height, traffic and airspace awareness are continuous
- [HF] Body sensations are unreliable in steep turns — trust the instruments; parallax error will be especially noticeable — the left and right turn will look like different attitudes entirely; brief the startle management response for spiral dive entry before the flight

*Forces in a Steep Turn* (10 minutes)
- Load factor and AoB: at 45°, load factor = 1.41 g; stall speed increases by √1.41 = +19%
- At 60°, load factor = 2 g; stall speed increases by √2 = +41%
- Implication: holding altitude in steep turns results in high AoA and increases stall speed significantly
- Overbanking tendency increases: more active rudder and aileron correction required at 60°
- Vertical component of lift reduced as bank increases: more backpressure required than in shallower turns

*Spiral Dive — Distinction and Recovery* (5 minutes)
- Stability coupling results in continuous yaw and roll; nose pitches down as vertical lift rolls away from upright
- Spiral dive symptoms: bank increases, nose drops below horizon, airspeed increases — not a steep turn or spin
- Recovery: close throttle (reduce acceleration), level wings with _coordinated_ aileron and rudder, ease out of the dive once wings are level — backpressure before wings level worsens the dive and stresses the airframe
- Disorientation risk: without a visible horizon, spatial disorientation may lead to loss of control

*Slipping and Skidding Turns* (5 minutes)
- Slip: too much bank for the rate of turn; ball displaced toward lower wing; outer wing stall risk
- Skid: too little bank for the rate of turn; ball displaced toward upper wing; inner wing stall risk; spin risk
- Visual illusion: in a skid, the apparent "rapid" increase in turn rate is an illusion - skidding will not turn the aircraft more quickly
- Deliberate sideslip revision: into-turn aileron, opposite (top) rudder; unreliable airspeed; nose-low attitude needed; control direction with aileron
- Note: skidding turns are discussed for awareness only — no pro-spin inputs are practiced by the student

*Turn Reversal and Sustained 360°* (5 minutes)
- Turn reversal (dutch rolls): coordinated roll in one direction, then reverse, coordinated roll in the opposite direction; smooth inputs; always coordinated; conducted at 20° AoB
- Sustained 360°: maintain 45° and 60° AoB throughout one full rotation; roll out within ±10° of entry heading
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Student briefs the instructor:*]
- Student obtains NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT; checks BOM radar; briefs conditions and suitability
- Student checks NOTAMs; identifies any relevant items
- Student reviews maintenance release; briefs instructor on all items
- Student briefs the planned flight: departure, transit, manoeuvre sequence, return, HASSELL minimum height, EFATO plan
- Student delivers pre-takeoff safety brief

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Receives brief; confirms or queries as needed
- Assumes instructor role to deliver the ground brief for advanced turning content above
- Returns to observer role for all other ground activities
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Observer/PIC Phase — Departure and Transit*]
Student operates as PIC. Instructor is an observer. Student conducts all startup, taxi, runup, radio calls, takeoff, and after-takeoff checks without prompting. Instructor may assist with circuit departure radio calls while the student focuses on climbout and transit tracking; instructor hands radio back to student at training area.

HASSELL check: student completes before the manoeuvre sequence begins.

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor Assumes Instructor Role — New Material*]

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- 45° steep turn: entry, maintenance, exit — patter bank, balance, backpressure, overbanking tendency; hold altitude ±100 ft, airspeed ±10 kts, rollout ±10°
- 60° steep turn: same sequence; patter increased backpressure and overbanking; demonstrate difference from 45°
- Spiral dive entry from steep turn: allow bank to increase, nose to drop, airspeed to build — patter symptoms; recovery: close throttle, level wings, ease out of the dive
- Slipping turn: demonstrate ball displaced toward lower wing; patter apparent decrease in turn rate on entry; aircraft tendency to roll level; correct to coordinated flight
- Skidding turn: demonstrate ball displaced toward upper wing; patter apparent acceleration in turn rate on entry; aircraft tendency to roll into the turn; correct to coordinated flight _Instructor demonstration only — no student practice_
- Dutch roll turn reversal from 20° AoB: smooth coordinated rolls in alternating directions
- Sustained 360° at 45° and 60° AoB

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- HASSELL check before sequence; every 15 minutes thereafter
- 45° steep turns left and right: maintain AoB ±5°, altitude ±100 ft, coordinated
- 60° steep turns left and right: maintain AoB ±5°, altitude ±100 ft, coordinated
- Spiral dive recovery: instructor initiates by increasing bank and lowering nose; student recovers without coaching
- Slipping turn: enter deliberately, maintain, recover to coordinated
- Dutch roll turn reversals from 20° AoB: smooth, coordinated, alternating directions
- Sustained 360° at 45° AoB and 60° AoB: roll out on entry heading ±10°

#text(size:12pt)[*Observer/PIC Phase — Return*]
Student conducts return transit and landing independently. Instructor may assist with inbound radio calls during the transit; hands radio back to student at circuit entry.
]

,common_errors:[
- *Altitude loss/gain in steep turn*: Check and correct bank first — if correct, adjust backpressure; correct horizon reference.
- *Backpressure before wings level in spiral dive recovery*: Level wings first; backpressure with banked wings tightens the spiral and stresses the airframe.
- *Chasing the balance ball in steep turns*: The ball will be slightly low in a steep turn — do not add inside rudder as a primary correction.
- *HASSELL*: HASSELL before the sequence begins, then every 15 minutes — not before each individual manoeuvre.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Leads Debrief* (10 min): Student reviews each manoeuvre; self-assesses against C standard; identifies what was correct, what was not, and why.
- *Instructor Supplements* (5 min): Adds any observations the student did not identify; reinforces skidding turn risks and why pro-spin inputs are not practiced.
- *Theory Check* (5 min): Student explains spiral dive recovery sequence and why the sequence matters.
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to L4.3*]
- *45° steep turn*: Bank ±10°; altitude ±150 ft; coordinated with occasional prompting
- *60° steep turn*: Bank ±10°; altitude ±150 ft; attempted with guidance
- *Spiral dive recovery*: Recognises entry; recovers correctly with minor prompting; sequence understood
- *Slipping turn*: Demonstrates entry and recovery with guidance; describes skidding turn risks
- *Dutch roll turn reversal*: Completes with minor correction to coordination or timing
- *Sustained 360°*: Completes at 45° with ±20° rollout error; 60° attempted

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (C) — required twice before solo*]
- *60° steep turn*: Bank ±10°; altitude ±200 ft; airspeed ±10 kts; coordinated throughout; rollout ±20° of target heading
- *45° steep turn*: Bank ±10°; altitude ±200 ft; airspeed ±10 kts; coordinated throughout; rollout ±20° of target heading
- *Spiral dive recovery*: Identified and recovered correctly without prompting; correct sequence every time
- *Slipping turn*: Demonstrated correctly; ball interpretation correct
- *Dutch roll turn reversal*: coordinated with some assistance; some altitude deviation acceptable
- *HASSELL*: Completed before sequence, then every 15 minutes, with one prompt
- *Student-as-PIC*: All trained flight portions without any instructor input

#text(size:12pt)[*Certificate Standard (C) — required before flight test*]
- *60° steep turn*: Bank ±5°; altitude ±100 ft; airspeed ±10 kts; coordinated throughout; rollout ±10° of target heading
- *Spiral dive recovery*: Identified and recovered promptly and correctly without prompting; correct sequence every time
- *Slipping turn*: Demonstrated correctly; ball interpretation correct; coordinated recovery smooth
- *Dutch roll turn reversal*: Smooth, timely, coordinated; minimal altitude deviation

- *HASSELL*: Completed before sequence, then every 15 minutes, without prompting
- *Student-as-PIC*: All trained flight portions without any instructor input

- *Outcome*: Recorded in training record as P, S or C with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible; ceiling >2500 ft AGL; surface wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct all manoeuvres above 2000 ft AGL; all recoveries complete above 1500 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: HASSELL before sequence includes forced landing area selection; no manoeuvres directly over populated areas
- *TEM*:
  - Spiral dive demonstration must be briefed before flight; student must confirm recovery sequence before entry
  - Instructor ready to take control immediately if bank exceeds 60° or nose drops more than 30° below horizon without recovery initiated
  - Monitor for spatial disorientation in sustained steep turns; pause and allow reorientation if required
  - Monitor for G-strain or discomfort; pause if required
  - Maintain SA regarding controlled airspace
- *Aircraft Limits*: Do not exceed Va in steep turns; avoid abrupt inputs at high bank angles; all manoeuvres per POH
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 105, 106, 165–168 (sideslip, spiral dive, load factor, stall speed in turns, skid/slip)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 36 (SA, stress and decision-making)
- Prepare for E10 (Scenario Based Stalling) next lesson:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 168–173 (stalling in all configurations, accelerated stall, spin entry)
  - Human Factors: Pg 35, 44–45, 48, 51 (false hypothesis, undesired aircraft states, countermeasures)
- Reflect:
  - "You are on base-to-final at 45° AoB at approach speed. What is your stall speed compared to level flight? What does this mean practically?"
  - "What is the single most important action in recovering from a spiral dive, and why does it have to come before pulling back?"
]
)

